	(313,1,'2018-12-08 11:37:12','2018-12-08 11:37:12','Are you loving your #AvoLife? Unless you’ve been living under a rock for the last year or two, you will know that avocados are the fruit of choice for… Well, just about everybody, actually. Yes, what was once the best-kept foodie secret, is now out of the shopping bag and onto your plate. But, do you know all there is to know about these small, green things? Here are five facts you need to get behind.\n\n1. AVOCADOS CONTAIN MORE POTASSIUM THAN BANANAS\nPotassium is an essential part of a balanced diet. In case you haven’t heard, it has a wealth of health (both mental and physical) benefits. For instance, research suggests that getting enough of this stuff could even lower your risk of having a heart attack. There’s no reason that you shouldn’t be fuelling up on the stuff on a regular basis.\n\nWhen you think of potassium, one specific fruit likely leaps to mind – the humble banana. Yes, this snack is rich in the good stuff, but there’s actually another fruit out there that has a whole load more potassium than that. A 100g serving of avocado gives you 14% of your recommended daily dose of potassium. On the other hand, a banana only gives you 10% in the same measurement. We rest our case.\n\n2. EATING THIS FRUIT COULD IMPROVE YOUR GUT HEALTH\nWant to improve your gut health? This is a hot topic right now and we’re fast discovering the many ways in which the condition of your gut actually affects the rest of your health at large. Of course, there are small steps you can take that will help to improve this area of your body and, specifically, the way in which it functions. Adding a few avocados to your shopping list could be a smart place to start. These fruits are rich in soluble fibre, which research shows helps to feed the friendly bacteria in your gut.\n\n3. AVOCADOS ARE PACKED WITH NUTRIENTS\nReady to revamp your lifestyle once and for all? We hear you. One of the easiest ways in which you can improve your diet and lead a healthier lifestyle is to choose snacks that are rich in the good things you need. Packing vitamins Bs, K, C, and E along with a range of essential nutrients, you can’t go far wrong with an avocado. Chomping down on one of these things could help you to boost your health and get more out of the food that you eat.\n\n4. THEY MAKE EXCELLENT DAIRY SUBSTITUTES\nLooking for a creamy and delicious substitute for dairy products? It could be staring you right in the face. One of the many reasons that avocados have soared in popularity in recent years is that they have a beautifully soft and cream-like texture.\n\nOf course, when you first start out leading a plant-based lifestyle, one of the major things that you may miss is dairy. Believe it or not, you can use avocados as a replacement for many of your favourite dairy products. Whether you puree the stuff and spread it on your toast or slice it thin to add to a salad, there’s no end of choices here. From whipping up rich sauces to creating a dairy-free dip, there are many uses for this fruit.\n\n5. THEY COULD HELP TO LOWER YOUR CHOLESTEROL\nAs your cholesterol levels soar, so do your chances of heart disease, stroke, and a whole load of other nasty health conditions that you’re going to want to avoid. Changing your overall diet and lifestyle could help you to get your levels in check before it’s too late.\n\nSome of the most impactful causes of this problem include eating meat, saturated fats, and dairy products. Leading a plant-based lifestyle can help you to avoid the issue. Of course, it’s not just about what you shouldn’t eat, but what you should eat too. Adding avocados to your diet could be the answer. Studies have found that these fruits can help to lower people’s cholesterol when eaten as part of a healthy and balanced diet.\n\nGood news! We will be serving your favourite avocado on toast at our new canteen at Cutlery Works, Kelham Island. Follow Shed on Instagram and Facebook for the latest details and our launch date!','Five interesting facts you might not know about avacados','','inherit','closed','closed','','86-autosave-v1','','','2018-12-08 11:37:12','2018-12-08 11:37:12','',86,'http://eatshed.local/86-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(314,1,'2018-12-08 11:38:13','2018-12-08 11:38:13','Are you loving your #AvoLife? Unless you’ve been living under a rock for the last year or two, you will know that avocados are the fruit of choice for… Well, just about everybody, actually. Yes, what was once the best-kept foodie secret, is now out of the shopping bag and onto your plate. But, do you know all there is to know about these small, green things? Here are five facts you need to get behind.\r\n<h2>1. AVOCADOS CONTAIN MORE POTASSIUM THAN BANANAS</h2>\r\nPotassium is an essential part of a balanced diet. In case you haven’t heard, it has a wealth of health (both mental and physical) benefits. For instance, research suggests that getting enough of this stuff could even lower your risk of having a heart attack. There’s no reason that you shouldn’t be fuelling up on the stuff on a regular basis.\r\n\r\nWhen you think of potassium, one specific fruit likely leaps to mind – the humble banana. Yes, this snack is rich in the good stuff, but there’s actually another fruit out there that has a whole load more potassium than that. A 100g serving of avocado gives you 14% of your recommended daily dose of potassium. On the other hand, a banana only gives you 10% in the same measurement. We rest our case.\r\n<h2>2. EATING THIS FRUIT COULD IMPROVE YOUR GUT HEALTH</h2>\r\nWant to improve your gut health? This is a hot topic right now and we’re fast discovering the many ways in which the condition of your gut actually affects the rest of your health at large. Of course, there are small steps you can take that will help to improve this area of your body and, specifically, the way in which it functions. Adding a few avocados to your shopping list could be a smart place to start. These fruits are rich in soluble fibre, which research shows helps to feed the friendly bacteria in your gut.\r\n<h2>3. AVOCADOS ARE PACKED WITH NUTRIENTS</h2>\r\nReady to revamp your lifestyle once and for all? We hear you. One of the easiest ways in which you can improve your diet and lead a healthier lifestyle is to choose snacks that are rich in the good things you need. Packing vitamins Bs, K, C, and E along with a range of essential nutrients, you can’t go far wrong with an avocado. Chomping down on one of these things could help you to boost your health and get more out of the food that you eat.\r\n<h2>4. THEY MAKE EXCELLENT DAIRY SUBSTITUTES</h2>\r\nLooking for a creamy and delicious substitute for dairy products? It could be staring you right in the face. One of the many reasons that avocados have soared in popularity in recent years is that they have a beautifully soft and cream-like texture.\r\n\r\nOf course, when you first start out leading a plant-based lifestyle, one of the major things that you may miss is dairy. Believe it or not, you can use avocados as a replacement for many of your favourite dairy products. Whether you puree the stuff and spread it on your toast or slice it thin to add to a salad, there’s no end of choices here. From whipping up rich sauces to creating a dairy-free dip, there are many uses for this fruit.\r\n<h2>5. THEY COULD HELP TO LOWER YOUR CHOLESTEROL</h2>\r\nAs your cholesterol levels soar, so do your chances of heart disease, stroke, and a whole load of other nasty health conditions that you’re going to want to avoid. Changing your overall diet and lifestyle could help you to get your levels in check before it’s too late.\r\n\r\nSome of the most impactful causes of this problem include eating meat, saturated fats, and dairy products. Leading a plant-based lifestyle can help you to avoid the issue. Of course, it’s not just about what you shouldn’t eat, but what you should eat too. Adding avocados to your diet could be the answer. Studies have found that these fruits can help to lower people’s cholesterol when eaten as part of a healthy and balanced diet.\r\n\r\n<strong>Good news! We will be serving your favourite avocado on toast at our new canteen at Cutlery Works, Kelham Island. Follow Shed on Instagram and Facebook for the latest details and our launch date!</strong>','Five interesting facts you might not know about avacados','','inherit','closed','closed','','86-revision-v1','','','2018-12-08 11:38:13','2018-12-08 11:38:13','',86,'http://eatshed.local/86-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(315,1,'2018-12-08 11:40:43','2018-12-08 11:40:43','On Sunday 14th October 2018, the plant pushers will be joining the Sheffield Organic Growers team as part of Apple Day. The event will include stunning orchard tours, apple tasting, and even a chance to make your own apple juice. Of course, Shed will be there offering a nutritious light lunch for attendees.\r\n\r\nTo celebrate the upcoming event, we thought we’d take a chance to relish in all things apple. In case you didn’t know, this particular fruit is jam-packed with a range of nutritional benefits. With that in mind, let’s take a look at why you should include apples in your diet and a delectable soup recipe to help you get started.\r\n<h2>1. High in nutrition</h2>\r\nCraving a sweet snack? The truth of the matter is that you can’t go far wrong with a humble apple. The nutritional makeup of this fruit is quite astounding. A medium apple bursts with high levels of vitamin C, vitamin K, potassium, and manganese. When eating an apple, it’s smartest to keep the skin on. There’s a whole load of fibre packed into the skin and you don’t want to miss out on all that nutrition.\r\n<h2>2. Weight loss benefits</h2>\r\nTrying to shift a few extra pounds can be tough at the best of times. We all know that the road toward a healthy weight is paved with exercise and eating well. However, sneaking some apples into your everyday meals could give you an extra edge.\r\n\r\nIn a revealing study, researchers found that participants who ate apple slices before a meal felt fuller than those who ate other apple products (such as sauce and apple juice). Eating slices of this fruit alongside a meal also caused participants to eat an average of 200 calories less than they usually would.\r\n<h2>3. Lower risk of diabetes</h2>\r\nIt goes without saying that type 2 diabetes is a huge threat. Diabetes UK estimates that around one in every 17 people has this health condition, although some cases will be undiagnosed. As though that weren’t troubling enough, the problem is growing. By the year 2025, it’s estimated that five million Britons will be diagnosed with the illness.\r\n\r\nChanging your diet and lifestyle could play a role. Adding fruit, including apples, to your diet could be one way to ward off this condition and protect your greater health. The results from a series of longitudinal studies suggested that those who ate higher amounts of fruit were less likely to develop type 2 diabetes at some point during their life.\r\n<h2>4. Reduced risk of cancer for women</h2>\r\nLeading a healthy lifestyle could give you better odds when it comes to the risk of developing cancer. The latest research suggests that including apples in your diet could lead to a lower risk level. One report notes that this theory could be particularly true when we’re talking about lung cancer in women.\r\n\r\nAs part of the Nurses’ Health Study and the Health Professionals’ follow-up study, the fruit consumption of thousands of men and women was taken into consideration. The results found that women who consumed at least one apple per day were less likely to develop lung cancer. However, the same results were not found in the male participants.\r\n<h2>5. Keep teeth healthy</h2>\r\nCould an apple a day keep the dentist away? The short answer is yes. While there are no dental cleansing benefits within the apple itself, biting into one of these things could make all the difference. The reason is that chewing and biting stimulate the saliva production in your mouth. That in itself helps to decrease the levels of harmful bacteria in your mouth and means that you can lower the risk of tooth decay.\r\n<h3></h3>\r\n<h2>Recipe: Celeriac and Apple Soup</h2>\r\nNow that it’s finally getting a little cooler, it’s officially soup season! Yes, there’s nothing quite as warming or enticing as coming home and sipping a hot cup of nourishing soup. Rather than relying on the tinned options, why not make your own? Here’s a quick recipe that bursts with flavour and even includes an apple twist. Try it for yourself.\r\n<h3>Ingredients</h3>\r\n1 tbsp rapeseed oil\r\n\r\n1 large white onion\r\n\r\n2 cloves of garlic\r\n\r\n2 sticks of celery\r\n\r\nFew sprigs of rosemary\r\n\r\n1 large head of celeriac\r\n\r\n2 Granny Smith apples\r\n\r\nLow-sodium veg stock\r\n\r\nPink Himalayan salt\r\n\r\nToasted pumpkin seeds\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Directions</h2>\r\n<strong>Step one: Prep your food</strong>\r\n\r\nFirst up, it’s time to do some prepping. Peel and slice the onion. Peel and roughly chop the celeriac. Chop the rosemary. Slice the celery sticks. And peel the garlic cloves.\r\n\r\n<strong>Step two: Heat things up</strong>\r\n\r\nPut a large pan on the hob on a medium heat. Add oil, onion, celery, and garlic. Sweat until soft and translucent. Add the chopped celeriac and rosemary, and then sweat for a further two minutes.\r\n\r\n<strong>Step three: Add some stock</strong>\r\n\r\nAdd the low-sodium vegetable stock and make sure it covers an inch above the contents of the pan. Put a lid on it and simmer until the celeriac is soft. Core the apples and grate into the pan.\r\n\r\n<strong>Step four: Get blending!</strong>\r\n\r\nUse a stick blender and blend until smooth. Finally, season your soup with a pinch of pink Himalayan salt and serve with toasted pumpkin seeds.\r\n\r\nLike what you see? Get social. Don’t forget to follow us on Facebook and Instagram for more plant-based news and updates.\r\n\r\nPhoto credit: Sheffield Organic Growers','5 surprising benefits of eating apples plus a unique soup recipe','','inherit','closed','closed','','306-revision-v1','','','2018-12-08 11:40:43','2018-12-08 11:40:43','',306,'http://eatshed.local/306-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
